#Anova among lake types for species diversity
Diversity <- lakes$Diversity
Status <- lakes$Status
lakedivfit <- aov(Diversity~Status)
lakedivfit

##

#Useful functions# resid(my.regression) gets you residuals You can then plot them using hist()

Note that fitted values are those drawn from you regression line (which becomes abline)

When you plot residuals against fitted values, you want to see similar variation across the whole plot: homoscedasticity. If the scatterplot is all bunched on one end and expands as you change in X, you see that variation changes as X does: that’s bad! (variance in Y changed as value of X changed)

gvla: a function that checks for the relationships in your data gvlma(my.regression)

If the output tells you that your regression fails to meet an assumption e.g. the relationship is non-linear, you change your data with a transformation (e.g. snormalize), try a different analysis, or simply acknowledge that an assumption was not met and why that’s okay for your work
